4. USING THE MOBILE APP – REGULAR USER FLOWS
------------------------------------------------------------

4.1 Granting usage permission (Screen Time access)
To measure your screen time, the app needs Android usage access.
Note: Android does not show this as a standard in-app Allow/Deny popup. The app opens Settings where you enable Usage Access manually.

Steps:
1. Open the app and go to the Time tab. If permission is missing, a banner or prompt will appear.
2. Tap “Grant permission” or similar button.
3. Android will navigate you to the “Usage access” or “Screen time” settings page.
4. Find Life Pattern Tracker in the list.
5. Toggle the permission ON or tap “Allow”.
6. Return to the app; it will start reading your usage statistics.

[Screenshot placeholder: Permission request banner in app]
[Screenshot placeholder: Android usage access settings screen]

4.2 Viewing daily screen time
1. Tap the Time tab in the bottom navigation.
2. At the top, see:
   - Today’s total screen time (e.g., “3h 10m”)
   - Comparison to your average (e.g., “+19m above avg”)
3. Scroll down to see:
   - Focus and productivity scores
   - Breakdown by category (Social, Productive, Games, Other)
   - Usage charts (today and 7-day trends)

[Screenshot placeholder: Time tab top section highlighting today’s total]
[Screenshot placeholder: Charts and category breakdown]

4.3 Setting daily app limits

4.3.1 Adding a new limit
1. Open the Time tab.
2. In the “Daily app limits” card, tap “Add limit”.
3. A sheet will open listing all installed apps on your device.
4. Use the search box to find a specific app if necessary.
5. Tap the app you want to limit (for example, a social media app).
6. In the “Daily limit” section:
   - Choose one of the preset chips (15, 30, 60, 120, 180, 240 minutes), OR
   - Tap the “Custom” chip to enter a custom number of minutes.
7. Tap “Save limit”.

Once saved:
- The app will monitor your usage for that app.
- When you reach your daily limit, you will receive a gentle notification (if permissions are granted).

[Screenshot placeholder: “Daily app limits” card with “Add limit” button]
[Screenshot placeholder: App picker sheet showing installed apps]
[Screenshot placeholder: Limit presets and Custom option]

4.3.2 Editing an existing limit
1. In the Time tab, look under “Daily app limits”.
2. Find the app limit card you want to change.
3. Inside the card, use:
   - The preset chips to quickly change the cap, or
   - The “Custom” chip to type a new limit (e.g., 75 minutes).
4. The new limit is saved after selection/confirmation.

[Screenshot placeholder: Existing limit card with chips and custom option]

4.3.3 Enabling/disabling gentle alerts
1. In the limit card for an app, find the “Gentle alerts” toggle.
2. Turn it ON to receive one daily notification when your limit is exceeded.
3. Turn it OFF to stop notifications for that app (the limit is still stored for display).

[Screenshot placeholder: Limit card with “Gentle alerts” switch]

4.4 Viewing habits and logging progress

4.4.1 Viewing your habits
1. Tap the Habits tab.
2. You will see a list of habits (Exercise, Sleep, Water, Mood, etc.).
3. Each habit shows:
   - Name
   - Completion percentage for the current week
   - Streak or other progress indicators

[Screenshot placeholder: Habits tab with list of habits]

4.4.2 Logging a habit
1. On the Habits tab, select the habit you want to log (depending on UI, either tap the habit or press a “Log” button).
2. Confirm the completion or enter required details (for example, number of glasses of water).
3. The weekly percentage and streak will update.

[Screenshot placeholder: Habit logging example]

4.4.3 Logging mood (if provided)
1. On the Habits tab, open the mood-related habit (or dedicated mood logging section).
2. Choose your mood rating (e.g., scale 1–10 or defined emoticons).
3. Save the entry.

The app uses mood data to generate more personalised insights.

[Screenshot placeholder: Mood logging interface]

4.5 Viewing insights and AI suggestions

4.5.1 Calculated insights
1. Open the Insights tab.
2. The top section shows automatically calculated insights, such as:
   - Changes in screen time compared to last week
   - Most used apps
   - Whether you are above or below your screen time goal

[Screenshot placeholder: Insights page with calculated insights]

4.5.2 AI coach suggestions
If the Gemini key is configured on the backend / app:
1. In the Insights tab, a section labelled “AI tips” or similar will appear.
2. Read the suggestions and follow the practical advice for:
   - Reducing screen time
   - Improving focus and productivity
   - Building better habits

[Screenshot placeholder: AI-generated tips in Insights]

4.6 Using the in-app assistant/chat
1. Tap the floating chat button (usually bottom-right) or open the Chat/Assistant from the interface.
2. Type your question about:
   - Screen time (“How is my screen time today?”)
   - Habits (“How is my habit progress this week?”)
   - Focus and productivity (“Why is my focus score low?”)
3. Wait for the assistant reply.
   - If AI is available, it uses your data to give suggestions.
   - If not, it falls back to built-in rule-based tips.

[Screenshot placeholder: Chat assistant panel with example questions and answers]

4.7 Managing account and settings
1. Tap the More tab.
2. Open the Account or Settings section.
3. From here, you may:
   - View your email / profile
   - Sign out of the app
   - Permanently delete your account (Danger zone)
   - View privacy information and terms (if provided)

[Screenshot placeholder: More tab – Account settings page]

4.7.1 Deleting your account (mobile user)
1. Open More → Account.
2. Scroll to the “Danger zone” section.
3. Tap “Delete account”.
4. Enter your current password to confirm.
5. Tap “Delete”.

What happens next:
- Your account is permanently removed from the server.
- Synced usage days, habit snapshots, support conversations/messages, and related account records are deleted.
- You are signed out immediately.

[Screenshot placeholder: Account screen Danger zone with Delete account]
[Screenshot placeholder: Delete account confirmation dialog with password field]

4.8 Notifications and permissions
1. On first use, the app may request notification permissions.
2. Allow notifications to receive:
   - Gentle limit alerts
   - Important reminders or updates
3. If you disable notifications in Android, limit alerts will no longer appear.

[Screenshot placeholder: Android notification permission prompt]

